# ============================================================================
# DOCUMENTATION AND GUIDELINES
# ============================================================================

# LINE ENDING EXPLANATION:
# =====================
#
# `eol=lf` - Ensures Unix line endings (LF, \n) on all platforms:
#   - Windows developers: Git converts CRLF (local) ↔ LF (repository)
#   - macOS/Linux developers: No conversion needed (already LF)
#   - Result: Repository is always LF, working directory uses native OS
#
# `eol=crlf` - Windows-specific files that REQUIRE CRLF:
#   - Batch files (.bat, .cmd): Windows batch interpreter requires CRLF
#   - PowerShell (.ps1): Usually works with LF but CRLF is more compatible
#
# `text=auto` - Auto-detect text files:
#   - Git automatically detects whether file is text or binary
#   - Applied to all files by default in `*`
#
# `binary` - Treat file as binary:
#   - No line ending conversion
#   - No text diffs
#   - Used for images, archives, serialized data
#

# DIFF STRATEGIES EXPLANATION:
# ===========================
#
# `diff=python` - Python-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=yaml` - YAML-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=json` - JSON-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=markdown` - Markdown-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=xml` - XML-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=bash` - Bash script-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=makefile` - Makefile-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=javascript` - JavaScript/TypeScript-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=toml` - TOML-specific diff highlighting
# `diff=sql` - SQL-specific diff highlighting
#

# MERGE STRATEGIES EXPLANATION:
# ============================
#
# `merge=ours` - In a merge conflict, prefer "ours" (current branch)
#   - Useful for lock files that should not be merged
#   - Changes from other branch are ignored
#
# `merge=union` - In a merge conflict, take both sides
#   - Useful for changelogs where entries are additive
#   - Prevents conflicts when multiple developers add entries
#

# EXPORT-IGNORE EXPLANATION:
# ==========================
#
# Files marked `export-ignore` are excluded when running:
#   - `git archive --format=tar main | tar xf -`
#   - GitHub release downloads
#   - Package distributions
#
# These are development/internal files not needed by end users
#

# ============================================================================
# CONFIGURATION NOTES
# ============================================================================

# This .gitattributes file ensures:
# ✓ Consistent LF line endings across all platforms
# ✓ Binary files are not corrupted by line ending conversion
# ✓ Proper diff display for language-specific files
# ✓ Correct merge behavior for lock files
# ✓ Development files excluded from distributions
# ✓ Archives (git archive) don't include unnecessary files

# Benefits:
# ✓ Windows developers don't see "all lines changed" due to CRLF
# ✓ No accidental binary file corruption
# ✓ Better diffs in GitHub, GitLab, etc.
# ✓ Cleaner git history
# ✓ Reproducible builds across platforms

# To verify attributes on a file:
#   git check-attr -a <filename>
#
# To debug line ending issues:
#   git config core.safecrlf true  # Warn before auto-conversion
#   git config core.autocrlf false # Manual control (recommended with .gitattributes)

